    "body": "Just give each their own extensions; .hb for handlebars files and .ejs\n\napp.engine('hb', engines.handlebars);\napp.engine('ejs', engines.ejs);\n\nNo?\n\n- Michael\n\nOn Tue, Oct 31, 2017 at 6:54 PM, Thomas (Pacific Consulting Group) <\nnotifications@github.com> wrote:\n\n> I'm kind of having the same problem with respect to this issue.\n>\n> So here's what happen.\n>\n> I have a set of html files that are predominantly using handlebars in\n> another platform.\n> In my current express setup, I'm using ejs to include 'header', 'footer'\n> or any other html snippet files.\n>\n> Now I wish to do the following:\n>\n> const express = require(\"express\");\n> const engines = require('consolidate');\n> app = express();\n> app.engine('html', engines.handlebars);\n> app.engine('html', engines.ejs);\n>\n> app.get(\"/\", function (req, res) {\n> res.render(\"index\", context); //index page here will go through handlebars\n> and populate the necessary markdown with properties in context and go\n> through ejs for the include syntax to work\n> });\n>\n> So that the the request will go through handlebars -> ejs when the view is\n> rendered.\n>\n> Apparently, this is not working. express can only recognise ejs.\n>\n> —\n> You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> <https://github.com/expressjs/express/issues/640#issuecomment-340727286>,\n> or mute the thread\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AE3lcXuI0t5_f94mv1_5Hd17eg5_gQQbks5sxvx9gaJpZM4QMjRK>\n> .\n>\n",
